50|$|FES is {{distinct}} from the presence of fat emboli. Symptoms usually occur 1-3 days after a traumatic injury and are predominantly pulmonary (shortness of breath, hypoxemia), neurological (agitation, delirium, or coma), dermatological (<b>petechial</b> rash), and haematological (anaemia, low platelets). The syndrome manifests more frequently in closed fractures of the pelvis or long bones. The <b>petechial</b> rash, which usually resolves in 5-7 days, {{is said to be}} pathognomonic for the syndrome, but only occurs in 20-50% of cases.|$|E
